1 (3) The obligation to make a free appropriate public education available to individuals with
2 disabilities 18 through 21 years of age who are incarcerated in an adult correctional facility applies
3 only to those individuals who, in their last educational placement prior to their incarceration in the
4 adult correctional facility:
5 (a) Were identified as being a child with a disability as defined in ORS 343.035; or
6 (b) Had an individualized education program as described in ORS 343.151.
7 (4) For purposes of subsection (3) of this section, “adult correctional facility” means:
8 (a) A local correctional facility as defined in ORS 169.005;
9 (b) A regional correctional facility as defined in ORS 169.620; or
10 (c) A Department of Corrections institution as defined in ORS 421.005.
11 (5) An otherwise eligible person under subsection (2) of this section whose 21st birthday occurs
12 during the school year shall continue to be eligible for a free appropriate public education for the
13 remainder of the school year.
14 (6) The person may apply to the board of directors of the school district of residence for ad-
15 mission after the 19th birthday as provided in subsection (1) of this section. A person aggrieved by
16 a decision of the local board may appeal to the State Board of Education. The decision of the state
17 board is final and not subject to appeal.
18 (7) Notwithstanding ORS 339.133 (2)(a), a school district shall not exclude from admission a child
19 located in the district solely because the child does not have a fixed place of residence or solely
20 because the child is not under the supervision of a parent, guardian or person in a parental re-
21 lationship.
22 (8) Notwithstanding subsection (1) of this section, a school district:
23 (a) May for the remaining period of an expulsion deny admission to the regular school to a
24 resident student who is expelled from another school district; and
25 (b) Shall for at least one calendar year from the date of the expulsion and if the expulsion is for
26 more than one calendar year, may for the remaining period of time deny admission to the regular
27 school program to a student who is under expulsion from another school district for an offense that
28 constitutes a violation of a school district policy adopted pursuant to ORS 339.250 (7).
29 (9) Notwithstanding the minimum age requirement prescribed by ORS 339.010 and 339.020, a
30 district school board may admit free of charge a child whose needs for cognitive, social and physical
31 development would best be met in the school program, as defined by policies of the district school
32 board, to enter school even though the child has not attained the minimum age requirement but is
33 a resident of the district.
